bsite=Ars Technica|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[CBS News]] releases an excerpt from an interview in which [[Gayle King]] asks [[Lisa Leslie]] whether rape allegations made against [[Kobe Bryant]] complicated the recently passed [[NBA]] star's legacy. After facing criticism from [[50 Cent]], [[Snoop Dogg]] and other social media users, King blamed CBS for selecting a \"salacious\" portion of the interview to share without context. For its part, the network said that the excerpt was not reflective of the \"thoughtful, wide-ranging interview\" that King had conducted.\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Gayle King criticizes employer CBS for sharing 'salacious' clip of Lisa Leslie defending Kobe Bryant|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/06/media/gayle-king-kobe-bryant-lisa-leslie-intl-scli/index.html|author=Toyin Owoseje|website=CNN Business|publisher=WarnerMedia|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! 8\n|[[ESPN]] basketball analyst Barry Booker receives criticism for referring to female gymnasts as \"scantily clad girls\" in a sidebar with lead announcer Richard Cross\u2014both of whom were presiding over that night's college basketball game between the [[Arkansas Razorbacks men's basketball|Arkansas Razorbacks]] and the [[Missouri Tigers men's basketball|Missouri Tigers]]\u2014while promoting [[SEC Network]]'s February 14 telecast of an [[Alabama Crimson Tide women's gymnastics|Alabama]]\u2013[[Arkansas Razorbacks gymnastics|Arkansas]] women's gymnastics meet. ESPN, the [[Southeastern Conference]] and former Arkansas gymnast Sydney McGlone (the latter of whom noted the remark sexualized gymnastics as the sport continues to deal with [[sexual abuse]] scandals involving trainers and physicians of gymnasts at the collegiate and professional levels) denounced Booker's comments; Booker later apologized for the remark.\n|<ref>{{cite news|title=ESPN analyst Barry Booker ripped for calling gymnasts 'scantily clad girls'|url=https://nypost.com/2020/02/10/espn-analyst-barry-booker-ripped-for-calling-gymnasts-scantily-clad-girls/|author=Samantha Previte|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|publisher=[[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp.]]|date=February 10, 2020|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! 9\n|The [[92nd Academy Awards]], presented from the [[Dolby Theatre]] in [[Hollywood]], airs on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. This was the second consecutive year that the broadcast did not have a host. The [[South Korea]]n-language comedy thriller ''[[Parasite (2019 film)|Parasite]]'' made history, winning for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], [[Academy Award for Best International Feature Film|Best International Feature Film]], [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]], becoming the first South Korean film to receive Academy Award recognition, as well as the first film not in the English language to win Best Picture. [[Netflix]], which set a record for having the most nominations from a streaming service and studio with 24, surpassing the 15 it received for the previous year's event, took home only two; its heavily touted ''[[The Irishman (2019 film)|The Irishman]]'', which was nominated in ten categories, was shut out in every single one. Meanwhile, just two days prior to the airing of the event, AMPAS and ABC came under fire for rejecting a commercial for Frida Mom which depicted a [[postpartum]] mother changing her own, [[nocturnal enuresis|visibly wet]], absorbent pad in the middle of the night; the academy felt it was too graphic to air during the telecast, citing guidelines laid out in AMPAS that state that, among other items, \"feminine hygiene products (and) adult diapers\" could not be advertised on the telecast. The rejection sparked outrage from women's groups and from [[Busy Philipps]], who posted the rejected ad on her [[Instagram]] account. Ratings wise, this telecast would average at least 23.6 million viewers and a 5.3 rating among the key ad-sales demo of adults 18\u201349, down 20 percent year-over-year in viewers and 31 percent in adults 18\u201349.\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston.com/culture/movies/2018/08/08/oscars-add-popular-film-category-sets-earlier-2020-date|title=Oscars add popular film category, sets earlier 2020 date|website=Boston.com|first=Lindsey|last=Bahr|date=August 8, 2018|accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://www.huffpost.com/entry/frida-mom-postpartum-ad-rejected-oscars-abc_l_5e3dcbedc5b6bb0ffc10df29 \"Mothers Push Back After Frida Mom Postpartum Ad Rejected By Oscars\"] from Huffington Post (February 7, 2020)</ref><br><ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/netflix-wins-two-oscars-irishman-leaves-empty-handed-1277795 \"Netflix Wins Two Oscars, 'The Irishman' Leaves Empty-Handed\"] from The Hollywood Reporter (February 10, 2020)</ref><ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/oscars-hit-all-time-low-tv-ratings-sunday-feb-9-2020-1278364 \"TV Ratings: Oscars Fall to All-Time Lows\"] from The Hollywood Reporter (February 10, 2020)</ref>\n|-\n! 11\n|''[[The Conners]]'' aired a special live episode the night of the [[2020 New Hampshire Democratic primary|New Hampshire primary]] on ABC, which incorporated voting results reported by [[ABC News]] as they became available into the storyline. The episode was performed twice for [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]]/[[Central Time Zone|Central]] and [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific Time]] viewers, the latter of which aired as Bernie Sanders was projected as the primary's winner, finishing at a 1.4 percentage point margin ahead of [[Pete Buttigieg]], and was delayed two minutes\u2014starting less than 10 seconds before the cast was set to start performing that version\u2014to allow a live election update.\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=\"The Conners\" to Air Live the Night of the New Hampshire Primary, Tuesday, Feb. 11|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2020/01/08/the-conners-to-air-live-the-night-of-the-new-hampshire-primary-tuesday-feb-11-996205/20200108abc03/|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=January 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018The Conners': Behind the Scenes of Two Live New Hampshire Primary-Focused Episodes|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/conners-behind-scenes-two-live-new-hampshire-primary-focused-episodes-1278914|author=Kirsten Chuba|periodical=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Billboard-Hollywood Reporter Media Group|date=February 11, 2020|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!rowspan=2| 12\n|[[Altice USA]] announces its intent to acquire the [[Sussex County, New Jersey|Sussex County]] and northern [[Warren County, New Jersey]] operations of telecommunications provider [[Service Electric]] for $150 million. The deal\u2014which does not include Service Electric's systems in eastern Pennsylvania, and [[Hunterdon County, New Jersey|Hunterdon]] and southern Warren counties in New Jersey, which will continue to be owned by the children of company founder John Walson Sr.\u2014is expected to be completed in the early fall of 2020.\n|<ref>[https://www.njherald.com/news/20200214/service-electric-to-be-acquired-by-nyc-based-altice-cable Service Electric to be acquired by NYC-based Altice cable] from New Jersey Herald (February 14, 2020)</ref>\n|-\n|Former [[National Hockey League]] player [[Jeremy Roenick]] announces via [[Twitter]] that he had been terminated by [[NBC Sports]] as an analyst on their [[NHL on NBC|NHL coverage]] two months after an appearance on a [[Barstool Sports]] podcast in which he made inappropriate comments about wife and NBC colleague [[Kathryn Tappen]], and fellow NBC NHL analyst [[Patrick Sharp]].\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeremy Roenick out at NBC after threesome remarks: \u2018What a joke!\u2019|url=https://nypost.com/2020/02/12/jeremy-roenick-out-at-nbc-after-threesome-remarks-what-a-joke/|author=Mollie Walker|periodical=New York Post|pu