19 departure as [[Viacom (2005\u20132019)|Viacom]] CEO upon its [[2019 merger of CBS and Viacom|re-merger]] with [[CBS Corporation|CBS]]) will succeed Vince Sadusky as Univision Communications's CEO upon the deal's closure.\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Davis Group Acquires Majority of Univision|url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/davis-group-acquires-majority-of-univision|author=Jon Lafayette|periodical=Broadcasting & Cable|publisher=Future US|date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Investor Group to Acquire Majority Stake in Univision, Wade Davis to Become CEO|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/investor-group-acquire-majority-stake-univision-wade-davis-become-ceo-1277183|author=Georg Szalai|periodical=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Billboard-Hollywood Reporter Media Group|date=February 25, 2020|accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Comcast]] announces its intent to acquire AVOD streaming service [[Xumo]]\u2014which will operate as an independent business within the Comcast Cable division upon closure\u2014from [[Panasonic]] and [[Meredith Corporation|Viant Technology]] for an undisclosed sum. The acquisition will likely see Xumo be used to market [[Xfinity]] and other Comcast services (such as programming from [[NBCUniversal Cable Entertainment Group|its]] [[NBC Sports Group|cable]] [[NBCUniversal Television Group#NBCUniversal Broadcast, Cable, Sports and News|networks]], and upcoming streaming service [[Peacock (streaming service)|Peacock]]), and provide infrastructure for Comcast's streaming VOD technology. The purchase comes as Comcast's [[NBCUniversal]] unit is also in discussions to purchase [[Walmart]]-owned VOD service [[Vudu]].\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Comcast Buys Ad-Supported Streaming Service Xumo|url=https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/comcast-buys-ad-supported-streaming-service-xumo|author=Jon Lafayette|periodical=Broadcasting & Cable|publisher=Future US|date=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[ABC News]] suspends correspondent [[David Wright (journalist)|David Wright]] and reassigns him from political reporting over non-neutral remarks he made in a video by conservative group [[Project Veritas]], including criticism of its cross-promotion of ABC parent [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]]'s TV and film content (primarily on its overnight and morning news programs, ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[World News Now]]'' and ''[[America This Morning]]''), and aspects of its [[White House]] and presidential campaign coverage. The suspension is criticized by fellow journalists due to Veritas' past reputation for trying to damage the careers of journalists investigating conservative causes as well as ongoing issues with mainstream news organizations restricting journalists' personal political opinions in the current political climate.\n|<ref>{{cite news|title=ABC News suspends correspondent David Wright after comments about Trump coverage, socialism, in Project Veritas sting|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/media/abc-news-suspends-correspondent-david-wright-after-project-veritas-sting/2020/02/26/764efc06-5849-11ea-9b35-def5a027d470_story.html|author=Paul Farhi|newspaper=The Washington Post|publisher=Nash Holdings LLC|date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ABC takes the bait and suspends a veteran correspondent over a bad-faith, right-wing hit job|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/abc/abc-takes-bait-and-suspends-veteran-correspondent-over-bad-faith-right-wing-hit-job|author=Courtney Hagle|website=[[Media Matters for America]]|date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!rowspan=3| 28\n|[[CBS Television Studios]] and [[Jerry Bruckheimer|Jerry Bruckheimer Productions]] announce a temporary suspension of production of the 33rd season of ''[[The Amazing Race (American TV series)|The Amazing Race]]'' due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] that had [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|recently spread into Europe]]. Filming had already been completed o