he was working on the film ''[[Iceman (1984 film)|Iceman]]'' in [[Vancouver, British Columbia|Vancouver]]; the victim alleges a friend of Hutton's watched the rape, before later also raping her. Hutton has denied the charges against him. ''Almost Family'' was unlikely to return in any case, as the low-rated and critically panned series quietly ended its first season with its finale being [[burning off|burned off]] on a Saturday night a week before.\n| <ref name=\"Cancelled\"/><ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/timothy-hutton-accused-raping-14-year-old-girl-1980s-1282206 \u201cTimothy Hutton Accused of Raping 14-Year-Old Girl in the 1980s\u201d] from The Hollywood Reporter (March 2, 2020)</ref>\n|-\n! 3\n|[[Nexstar Media Group]] announces it has completed deals to trade [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]-affiliated [[KCPQ]] and MyNetworkTV-affiliated [[KZJO]] in Seattle and Fox-affiliated [[WITI (TV)|WITI]] in Milwaukee to [[Fox Television Stations]] in exchange for Fox's Charlotte duopoly ([[WJZY]] and [[WMYT-TV]]) and cash. In Milwaukee, the sale returns WITI to the Fox portfolio after [[Local TV LLC]] purchased it and others from Fox in 2007, and finally gives Fox a longtime quest to enter the Seattle television market after six years, where it attempted to [[KBCB|acquire a station]] (that would have stripped KCPQ of its affiliation) that lead to a standoff between Fox and then-owner [[Tribune Broadcasting]] that later resulted in a renewal deal for KCPQ and Fox abandoning the sale at the last minute.   \n|<ref>[https://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/nexstar-media-completes-station-deals-with-fox Nexstar Media Completes Station Deals with Fox] ''Broadcasting & Cable'', March 2, 2020</ref>\n|-\n! 5\n|On the same day [[YouTube TV]] signed a long-term renewal deal with [[Fox Sports Networks]] joint-venture parent Diamond Sports Group (co-owned by [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] and [[Entertainment Studios]]), the provider drops three of the group's regional sports networks, [[Fox Sports West and Prime Ticket|Fox Sports West, Prime Ticket]] and [[YES Network]], which collectively hold rights to eight Los Angeles- and New York-based teams across the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]], [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]], [[National Hockey League|NHL]], [[Major League Soccer]] and [[Major League Baseball]]. The renewal for the 13 unaffected Fox Sports Networks services follows a temporary contract extension signed on February 28, during distribution negotiations between the companies, and amid [[Dish Network]]/[[Sling TV]] and [[FuboTV]] having dropped all of the group's networks\u2014which hold the local rights to 43 teams across the NBA, NHL, and MLB\u2014from their lineups.\n|<ref>{{cite news|title=YouTube TV is losing many regional sports channels and fans are furious|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2020/02/youtube-tv-fox-regional-sports-sinclair-reaction|author=Nick Schwartz|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett|date=February 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=YouTube TV Keeps Fox Regional Sports Networks on Air as Sinclair Talks Continue|url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/youtube-tv-fox-rsn-extension-sinclair-1203519821/|author=Todd Spangler|periodical=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=February 29, 2020}}</ref><br><ref>[https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/youtube-tv-sinclair-19-fox-rsns-drops-networks-1203524811/ YouTube TV Inks Deal for 19 Fox Regional Sports Nets With Sinclair, Drops YES and Two Others] ''Variety'', March 5, 2020</ref>\n|-\n!rowspan=2| 6\n|The government of [[Austin, Texas]] announces the cancellation of the 2020 edition of the [[South by Southwest]] conference (which was scheduled to be held from March 13 to March 22) due to the aforementioned [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]], which had recently spread into the state of Texas. Prior to the announcement, the owners of certain streaming services (including [[Netflix]], [[Apple TV+]], and [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime Video]]) announced that they had pulled out of the conference, resulting in the cancellation of numerous television show and film premieres. \n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/sxsw-canceled-coronavirus-2020-austin-1203526422/|title=SXSW 2020 Canceled Amid Coronavirus Fears|last=Low|first=Elaine|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 6, 2020|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|According to a report by [[Reuters]], [[Gray Television]] makes an offer to purchase [[Tegna Inc.]] at a price of $8.5 billion. Later in the day, [[Apollo Global Management]] matched Gray's offer at $20 per share in what would be an all-cash transaction, an offer matched by [[Entertainment Studios|Allen Media Broadcasting]] on March 11. A successful bid by Gray would put the owner of mostly smaller-market stations in cities such as [[WFAA|Dallas-Fort Worth]], [[KUSA (TV)|Denver]], [[WUSA (TV)|Washington, D.C.]], and its home-base of [[WXIA|Atlanta]], but would require Gray to sell stations in some markets, including [[Louisville]] and [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia]]. Gray pulls the offer on March 19 after its stock price is halved due to [[Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus-related market volatility]].\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.poynter.org/business-work/2020/gray-television-just-offered-8-5-billion-to-buy-tegna-what-happens-next/|title=Apollo and Gray Television match offers to buy Tegna. What happens next?|last=Tompkins|first=Al|work=[[Poynter Institute]]|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Byron Allen Makes $8.5B Cash Bid For Broadcaster Tegna|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/byron-allen-bid-broadcaster-tegna-1202880413/|author=Jill Goldsmith|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! 10\n|The effects of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]] continue to grow, especially for live and taped talk shows and upcoming series. [[20th Century Fox Television]] shut down production on Fox's upcoming ''[[NeXt (2020 TV series)|NeXt]]'' after a crew member came in contact with the coronavirus and might have affected other employees on the [[Chicago]]-based set, leaving a delay for the mid-season series possible despite much of its first season already being in the can. ''[[Dr. Phil (talk show)|Dr. Phil]]'' and ''[[The Wendy Williams Show]]'' both then announce that their shows will now tape without audiences, with [[Wendy Williams|Williams]] especially vulnerable due to a number of recent health issues. The daytime series of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] and [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]] then followed suit, with ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'', ''[[Live with Kelly and Ryan]]'', ''[[Tamron Hall (talk show)|Tamron Hall]]'' and ''[[Strahan, Sara and Keke]]'' all now taping without studio audiences. [[Disney+]] later announced that [[Marvel Studios]]\u2019 ''[[The Falcon and the Winter Soldier]]'' would shut down production in both [[Prague]] and [[Atlanta]] due to the outbreak until further notice, leaving its upcoming debut in question after it was announced for a 2020 debut on the streaming service.\n|<ref>[https://deadline.com/2020/03/next-fox-series-coronavirus-chicago-production-1202879094/ \u201cCoronavirus Hits Chicago Production Of Fox\u2019s \u2018NeXt\u2019; Crew Member Tests Positive For COVID-19\u201d] from Deadline (March 10, 2020)</ref><ref>[https://deadline.com/2020/03/jeopardy-wheel-of-fortune-film-without-audience-because-of-coronavirus-concerns-1202878109/ \u201c\u2018Wendy Williams Show\u2019 Joins \u2018Dr. Phil\u2019, \u2018Jeopardy!\u2019, \u2018Wheel Of Fortune\u2019 Shooting Without Audiences Amid Coronavirus Concerns \u2013 Update\u201d] from Deadline (March 10, 2020)</ref><br><ref>{{cite news|url=https://pagesix.co