s [[Ed Sullivan Theater]] studio) as a precaution days later. (WCBS/CBSN New York and ''Inside Edition'' resumed limited production operations from Broadcast Center during the week of March 23.)\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/culture/media/2020/03/11/cbs-news-shutters-office-after-two-employees-get-coronavirus|title=CBS News shutters office after two employees get coronavirus|last=Bauder|first=David|date=11 March 2020|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|The [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] [[Suspension of the 2019\u201320 NBA season|suspends the remainder of its 2019\u201320 season]] \"until further notice\" after [[Utah Jazz]] [[Center (basketball)|center]] [[Rudy Gobert]] (and later on March 12, fellow player and [[shooting guard]] [[Donovan Mitchell]]) tested presumptive positive for the coronavirus, resulting in the cancellation\u2014just prior to tip-off\u2014of a game in which the Jazz were facing the host city [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] at [[Chesapeake Energy Arena]] (all personnel associated with the Jazz organization, as well as teams they played within the last 10 days [including the Thunder], are quarantined until they are cleared), effectively leaving a large scheduling hole for [[NBA TV]], [[NBA on ESPN|ESPN]], [[NBA on TNT|TNT]] and the league's [[regional sports network]] partners. Ironically, two days earlier, Gobert jokingly touched equipment belonging to the media during a press conference after the Jazz's loss to the [[Toronto Raptors]], along with reports from other players who came into contact with him, putting its last ten road games the Jazz played against its opponents in question due to the possibility of more people being infected through Gobert.\n|<ref>[https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28887560/nba-suspends-season-further-notice-player-tests-positive-coronavirus \u201cNBA suspends season until further notice after player tests positive for the coronavirus\u201d] from ESPN (March 11, 2020)</ref>\n|-\n!rowspan=4| 12\n|Following the NBA's lead of the day prior, several other sports leagues across the United States announce a temporary suspension of play in an attempt to slow the spread of the coronavirus. [[Major League Soccer]] suspends all games for 30 days, while the [[National Hockey League|NHL]] announces an indefinite suspension of league activity, which was later followed in the day by [[Major League Baseball]]'s announcement that it has suspended its spring training games and delayed the start of their [[2020 Major League Baseball season|2020 regular season]] (originally scheduled to begin March 26) by at least two weeks. The suspension of the three leagues adds another large schedule void for [[NBC Sports]], ESPN, Fox Sports, [[Univision]], and the leagues' regional sports network partners. In addition, several [[College basketball#Conferences|NCAA basketball conference tournaments]] are canceled, including Division I basketball tournaments from the [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]], [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]], [[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]], [[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12]] and the [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]]; the [[Big East Conference|Big East]] was the only major NCAA athletic conference to initially go forward with that day's tournament play, before later canceling its tournament as well. Later that day, all scheduled NCAA tournaments for their winter and spring sports were canceled outright, including the men's and women's basketball tournaments which were set to be broadcast by [[NCAA March Madness (TV program)|CBS/Turner Sports]] and ESPN respectively. Later that evening officials with the [[PGA Tour]] announced that after the completion of [[The Players Championship]] it will cancel the next three events on the PGA Tour schedule, including the [[Valspar Championship]], the [[WGC Match Play|WGC-Dell Technologies Match Play]] and the [[Valero Texas Open]], emptying the schedule for [[Golf Channel]]; on March 13, the [[2020 Masters Tournament]] would become the latest event to announce its postponement, yet another setback for ESPN and its international broadcasts partners. The revived [[XFL (2020)|XFL]] officially ended its season and canceled the remainder of its games, but plans to return in 2021 and has not ruled out holding its [[2020 XFL Championship Game|championship game]] if conditions allow; the league announced on April 10 that it was suspending operations indefinitely. \n|<ref>[https://www.prosoccerusa.com/mls/major-league-soccer-reportedly-suspends-season-until-further-notice-amid-coronavirus-scare/ \u201cMajor League Soccer suspends season 30 days amid coronavirus scare\u201d] from Pro Soccer USA (March 12, 2020)</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NHL set to suspend season amid coronavirus pandemic|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/12/nhl-set-to-suspend-season-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/|author=Brett Cyrgalis|newspaper=New York Post|publisher=News Corp.|date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><br><ref>{{cite news|title=Power 5 leagues cancel conference tournaments|url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28891602/big-ten-sec-american-cancel-conference-tournaments|agency=ESPN News Services|website=ESPN|publisher=ESPN Inc.|date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=https://admin.bigten.org/news/2020/3/12/mens-basketball-big-ten-conference-statement.aspx|title=Big Ten Conference Statement|work=[[Big Ten Conference]]|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><br><ref>{{cite news|title=MLB expected to suspend spring training indefinitely because of coronavirus pandemic|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-12/mlb-suspends-spring-training-indefinitely-coronavirus-pandemic|author=Bill Shaikin|author2=Jorge Castillo|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Los Angeles Times Communications LLC|date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>[https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28894497/pga-tour-cancels-players-championship-first-round \"PGA Tour cancels Players Championshi